<div class="p-4 rounded-lg border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10 my-6">
  <p class="text-sm text-indigo-400 font-medium mb-1">💡 Parent Tip</p>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Never correct spelling harshly during a game. If a child plays an invalid word, gently say "that's a creative try — let's look it up together!" Making mistakes safe keeps kids wanting to play.</p>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Simplified Rules for Young Players</h2>

<p>These house rules make Scrabble accessible for younger children while preserving the core word-building experience:</p>

<div class="space-y-3 my-6">
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Open racks</span> — Place tiles face up so parents can offer hints without giving away the answer. This removes frustration while building independence.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Fewer tiles</span> — Start with 5 tiles instead of 7. Less overwhelming, and turns go faster keeping attention high.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Dictionary on the table</span> — Let kids look up words freely. This turns the game into active learning rather than a test.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">No challenges</span> — Accept any reasonably spelled word. If it is close enough, count it. Strictness kills enthusiasm.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Bonus for long words</span> — Give extra praise (or bonus points) for any word longer than 4 letters to encourage ambition.
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Educational Benefits</h2>

<p>Scrabble develops multiple cognitive skills simultaneously, making it far more educational than passive screen time. Here is what children gain from regular play:</p>

