    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-lg border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/10">
    <h3 class="font-semibold text-blue-400 mb-2">Thinking Skills</h3>
    <ul class="text-sm text-gray-300 space-y-1 list-disc list-inside">
      <li>Mental arithmetic (scoring)</li>
      <li>Strategic planning (tile placement)</li>
      <li>Pattern recognition (letter combos)</li>
      <li>Problem solving under constraints</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<p>Studies consistently show that children who play word games regularly score higher on standardised reading tests. The key difference from flashcards or worksheets is motivation — kids want to play Scrabble because it is genuinely fun.</p>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Family Game Tips</h2>

<p>The best way to keep kids engaged is making game night a positive ritual rather than a competitive pressure situation. These approaches work well for mixed-age families:</p>

<div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
<table class="w-full text-sm">
  <thead><tr class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800"><th class="p-2 text-left">Strategy</th><th class="p-2 text-left">Why It Works</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td class="p-2">Team up younger kids with adults</td><td class="p-2">They contribute ideas without bearing full responsibility</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2">Celebrate the word, not the score</td><td class="p-2">Shifts focus from winning to creating, reducing tears</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="p-2">Use a 2-minute sand timer</td><td class="p-2">Keeps pace moving so younger kids do not lose interest</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2">Allow "helper" tiles from the bag</td><td class="p-2">Stuck kids can draw an extra tile, keeping flow going</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="p-2">End after 30 minutes regardless</td><td class="p-2">Kids remember games fondly when they end before boredom</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Building Vocabulary Through Play</h2>

<p>The magic of Scrabble for learning is the natural repetition. Children encounter the same high-frequency words repeatedly and gradually absorb new ones from opponents' plays.</p>

<div class="p-4 rounded-lg border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10 my-6">
  <p class="text-sm text-indigo-400 font-medium mb-1">💡 Growth Strategy</p>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">After each game, pick one interesting word that was played and look up its meaning together. Write it on a fridge magnet or family word wall. Over months, this builds an impressive vocabulary bank — painlessly.</p>
</div>

<p>Start with common two and three-letter words that score well. Once children master these building blocks, longer words come naturally.</p>

